message.content:
A cairn is a man-made pile of stones that is used as a marker or landmark.
The stones in a cairn can be various colors, depending on their natural composition and the location of the cairn.
Cairns can range in size from a small pile of pebbles to a large structure several feet tall.
The stones in a cairn are often rough or unevenly shaped, giving the structure a natural look.
Cairns can often be found in remote, wilderness areas, where they serve as a guide for hikers or as a way to mark a special location.
They can also be found in coastal areas, where they may have been built as a navigation aid for sailors.
Some cultures use cairns as a form of spiritual or religious marker, such as the Inukshuk in Inuit culture.
